They may not be the most talented, but the Broncos just may have proved they are one of the league‚Äôs most mentally tough teams.

Hangover? That‚Äôs for the weak. Not for a team led by Bo Nix, a remarkably strong-willed rookie quarterback. The Broncos bounced back from their devastating loss last week at Kansas City to whip the Atlanta Falcons, 38-6 in an NFL cross-conference game played on a spectacular mid-November Sunday afternoon at Empower Field at Mile High.

Coming off a blocked, close-range feld goal on the final play that turned 17-16 victory into 16-14 defeat, the Broncos could have gone either way Sunday against Atlanta.

Let that excruciating setback linger to the point the team lost momentum.

Or play inspired from knowing they had outplayed the two-time defending and then undefeated Chiefs, and deserved to win.

‚ÄúIt still gets back to the players, the makeup,'' said Broncos' head coach Sean Payton. "It gets back to the things we keep talking about: The grit, the toughness. It‚Äôs a team that‚Äôs different than a year ago in that it has that. Their response was really good.‚Äù

Nix said it took no time at all to move on from last week's heartbreak.

"At the end of the game, you could have lined us all up and we could have played another four-quarter game against another team,'' Nix said about the 16-14 loss to Kansas City last week. "We wanted to go right back into the fire. When you lose a game like that you feel like, man, that one was stolen from us but I want to get right back on the field and go out there and play a game,

"That's how we felt this week. We had a great week of practice. Our preparation was phenomenal. Offense, defense, special teams we prepared like crazy. We fixed our mistakes that we wanted fixed. We came out and played with great effort, great intensity, great love for the guys around you.

The more Nix spoke as he answered the question, the more you could sense his intensity. He is the leader of his team and his personality and uber focus on winning a football game means he is leading the proper way.

"He's a special dude,'' said left tackle Garett Bolles. "He's relentless, he's smart, he's disciplined. That's what you want as a quarterback. And when you that type of guy back there and us up five up front giving him time to throw the ball, he's unbelievable. He can deliver the rock to our playmakers. We go as far as he's playing. If he keeps playing like that, we're a tough team to beat."

Waymo, the driverless car company run by Google parent company Alphabet, already operates autonomous vehicles in Los Angeles, San Francisco, and Phoenix. But soon, Waymo rides will be available in Atlanta and Austin. 

The Georgia and Texas Waymo experiences, set to launch early next year, will be a bit different than what California and Arizona riders encounter. Thanks to a partnership between former enemies Waymo and Uber, riders in Atlanta and Austin will be required to use the Uber app to hail a robo-car. Even though they may request a Waymo via the Uber app, Austin and Atlanta users will not be guaranteed one. Riders can decline a Waymo in those cities, or update their settings so they never receive a self-driving vehicle.

Uber will manage and dispatch a fleet of Waymo‚Äôs fully autonomous, all-electric Jaguar I-PACE vehicles that will grow to hundreds over time. Uber will also be responsible for the Waymo depots in Atlanta and Austin, as well as cleaning and vehicle repair. Waymo, on the other hand, will remain in charge of the car‚Äôs testing and operation, including roadside assistance and rider support functions.

post_body_text: Uber announced Friday it is expanding its partnership with Alphabet‚Äôs Waymo to offer robotaxi rides in Austin, Texas, and Atlanta beginning in early 2025. Dara Khosrowshahi, Uber CEO, discusses customer's willingness to accept an autonomous vehicle. Find more at the #linkinbio. #cnbc
GoogleAudioText: What is the willingness of people to order a autonomous Uber? Well, people are very open to it. And we're seeing actually the percentage of accept rates when offered an autonomous vehicle going up generally. There are some people who aren't ready for it. But I think the more you see these cars in the street, the more you see how safe they are, how cool they are. The acceptance rates are going to go higher and higher. And we make sure with our technology to dispatch the car to you when there's a pickup zone or a drop off zone that's convenient. So we want to make sure that the experience is a top experience as well. And we think with that kind of experience, more and more people will want to experience autonomous. Tara, I'm guessing at this point, for those who, as you say, might be a little reticent, you probably have some kind of 30-second pitch on what they can expect or how they should feel about it if they're taking a ride for the first time. Yeah, we tell them a little bit about the car itself, what the experience is like, what the pickup and then drop off is like. And people are very open to it. And again, I think if you take a ride, and we're very much looking forward to the folks in Austin, Atlanta taking a ride, they will want to take another and another.

Rideshare company Lyft launched a new pilot program that will kick into gear on Thursday to provide drivers with more security.

The ‚ÄòRider Verification‚Äô program will verify a passenger‚Äôs identity before a driver picks them up. According to a news release, the company will test the program in nine cities: Seattle, Detroit, Jacksonville, Houston, Atlanta, Phoenix, Chicago, Denver, and Miami.

Rider Verification works by cross-referencing rider information with third-party data sources to confirm the person requesting a ride is who they claim to be.

According to Lyft, it will be seamless for most riders. Most will be verified passively and won‚Äôt need extra steps. Under the pilot program, drivers can view a rider‚Äôs name, verification status, rating, and profile photo before accepting a request.

GoogleAudioText: Ok, ride share company, Uber. They are rolling out a new service today. They announced plans to launch a shuttle bus service. This is how it works. First of all, it's called Uber shuttle and this will take riders to and from places like the airport concert venues and sports stadiums. And riders can actually book up to five seats and a shuttle from a central location to an event or the airport for less than the regular price of an Uber ride space can be booked up to a week in advance and Uber is planning to partner with some local shuttle companies with commercially licensed drivers. The service is expected to roll out this summer in select cities including Chicago, Pittsburgh, Charlotte, and Miami right now. No word on when that service will roll right on to our city here in Atlanta.

Black Wolf is the latest service catering to the crime hysterical, the type of person who views American cities as descending into a Mad Max-style violent free-for-all. The service pitches itself to executive-types who might need bodyguard protection, and also to "women, school kids, and regular people who want peace of mind in this crazy world," according to its website. The app even offers a "school shuttle driver" service, which is a "door-to-door solution for parents juggling work and family."

It‚Äôs #WomensHistoryMonth, so we‚Äôre keeping the celebration going! Throughout March, we‚Äôll be spotlighting domestic workers and sharing more stories of the incredible women in our movement who fight every day to build a better future for domestic workers. 

Alicia Cleveland is a nanny of 15 years from Atlanta, Georgia. As a mother to three children, Alicia has done it all, from elderly care to driving for Lyft and Uber alongside her current role as a caregiver to two young kids.

Although Alicia loves care work, she has gotten used to working multiple jobs to make ends meet because nannying simply doesn‚Äôt pay enough. She got involved with We Dream In Black, NDWA‚Äôs initiative focused on building Black domestic worker power, through a co-worker and hasn‚Äôt looked back since. Meeting like-minded care workers who believe in the same changes that she does has motivated her to keep fighting ‚Äì we‚Äôll fight with her every step of the way.

post_body_text: NEW FEATURE üì± Uber rolled out an option Wednesday -- across the metro -- for riders and drivers to record audio during their trip. You'll need to activate the feature to use it.
The audio recording can be started by the driver or passenger.
GoogleAudioText: Miraculous moments in Turkey as researchers find another survivor nine days after a devastating earthquake struck the region today, a 42 year old woman was rescued from the rubble of a building in southern Turkey and it is nothing short of a miracle. The death toll in Turkey and Syria is now more than 40,000. At least 35,000 of those deaths were in Turkey alone, making the earthquakes the deadliest in that nation's history. 10s of thousands of survivors are now homeless. And hungry volunteers say they are feeding thousand 1000 people a day in Metro Atlanta. The donations to help earthquake victims have been pouring in. Take a look at this operation underway in North Cross, where boxes and boxes of humanitarian aid are arriving by the truckload. We're talking about coats, clothing, baby items and blankets coming in from all over the region. It's just amazing to see how us as humans in general can get together. Actually, we have this capability of getting together and supporting each other in these hard times Without Borders. The group is in daily contact with leaders on the ground in Turkey. The current needs include new winter tents, new weatherproof sleeping bags and generators. Donation drop offs will continue through Sunday, but there is a continued need for monetary donations as families work to rebuild.
